{"repo": "marcomusy/vedo", "pull_number": 1291, "instance_id": "marcomusy__vedo-1291", "issue_numbers": [1289], "base_commit": "e225d3a3ff34016d8237ffbf78eee89b92125d6c", "patch": "diff --git a/vedo/utils.py b/vedo/utils.py\nindex 1459b779..b8264fd7 100644\n--- a/vedo/utils.py\n+++ b/vedo/utils.py\n@@ -1164,15 +1164,22 @@ def andrews_curves(M, res=100) -> np.ndarray:\n \n \n ###########################################################\n-def numpy2vtk(arr, dtype=None, deep=True, name=\"\"):\n+def numpy2vtk(arr, dtype=None, deep=True, name=\"\", as_image=False, dims=None):\n     \"\"\"\n-    Convert a numpy array into a `vtkDataArray`.\n+    Convert a numpy array into a `vtkDataArray` or `vtkImageArray`.\n+\n     Use `dtype='id'` for `vtkIdTypeArray` objects.\n+    Use `as_image=True` and specify the dimensions with the `dims` keyword to generate\n+    a `vtkImageArray` object suitable for use with the volume constructor directly.\n     \"\"\"\n     # https://github.com/Kitware/VTK/blob/master/Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/util/numpy_support.py\n     if arr is None:\n         return None\n \n+    if as_image and dims is None:\n+        vedo.logger.error(\"must set dimensions (dims keyword) when requesting an image\")\n+        raise RuntimeError()\n+\n     arr = np.ascontiguousarray(arr)\n \n     if dtype == \"id\":\n@@ -1191,6 +1198,18 @@ def numpy2vtk(arr, dtype=None, deep=True, name=\"\"):\n \n     if name:\n         varr.SetName(name)\n+\n+    if as_image:\n+        # Assuming this is meant to be used with a volume\n+        varr.SetName(\"input_scalars\")\n+\n+        img = vtki.vtkImageData()\n+        img.SetDimensions(*dims[:3])\n+        img.GetPointData().AddArray(varr)\n+        img.GetPointData().SetActiveScalars(varr.GetName())\n+\n+        return img\n+\n     return varr\n \n def vtk2numpy(varr):\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Allow creation of volumes without deep copy of input object\nI am working with fairly large NumPy arrays (around ~2GiB) and I need to create volumes from them.\nIn order to keep memory usage low, I'd like to be able to pass the arrays to the volume constructor without it automatically duplicating the underlying array.\n\nThe code path that leads to the copying seems to be through [this](https://github.com/marcomusy/vedo/blob/ad94404161a8637f37831b48c6557d5e7e7a24e5/vedo/volume.py#L147) and then [this](https://github.com/marcomusy/vedo/blob/ad94404161a8637f37831b48c6557d5e7e7a24e5/vedo/utils.py#L1190). My arrays are already in F order so both `input_obj.ravel('F')` and `np.ascontiguousarray(arr)` lead to simple views.\n\nI am currently resorting to manually changing the function defaults at runtime which is very ugly and fragile:\n\n```\nvedo.utils.numpy2vtk.__defaults__ = (None, False, \"\")\n```\n\nI understand that managing the memory manually and ensuring it outlives the volume object is a bit of a more advanced and error-prone use case, but I was wondering if you'd consider hoisting the deep copy parameter up to the volume constructor.\nUnfortunately, hoisting it could lead to some confusion in cases where `deep=False`, `input_obj` is a C-order array, and a copy still occurs but that could be documented as `deep` only being reliable when set to `True`.\n", "hints_text": "Sorry for the delay in replying. Would be ok to modify the numpy2vtk() only. to generate a vtk object that could be used to initialize the Volume?\nDo you mean something like this:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nimport vedo\n\narray = np.random.randint(0, 255, (100, 100, 100), np.uint8)\nvtk_image_array = vedo.utils.numpy2vtk(array)\nvolume = vedo.Volume(vtk_image_array)\n```\n\nIf so, that'd work great, yes!\nYes! you may want to add additional keyword arguments in `vedo.utils.numpy2vtk(...)`.\nPull requests are welcome! :)\n\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Sorry for the delay in replying. Would be ok to modify the numpy2vtk() only. to generate a vtk object that could be used to initialize the Volume?\nDo you mean something like this:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nimport vedo\n\narray = np.random.randint(0, 255, (100, 100, 100), np.uint8)\nvtk_image_array = vedo.utils.numpy2vtk(array)\nvolume = vedo.Volume(vtk_image_array)\n```\n\nIf so, that'd work great, yes!\nYes! you may want to add additional keyword arguments in `vedo.utils.numpy2vtk(...)`.\nPull requests are welcome! :)\n\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/marcomusy/vedo/commit/92ab317d130e18d3a02af85956145d1c2ecb3e2f"], "created_at": "2026-02-02T17:09:30Z"}
